### Summary of enzymes involved

  • AOSD is a diagnosis of exclusion;

  • When to suspect: Any adult with daily or twice daily fever spikes with evanescent, salmon pink, non pruritic rash (which disappears with settling fever)

  • Also, arthritis, #lymphadenopathy , sore throat and #splenomegaly

  • Rash disappears during afebrile periods; present on trunk and extremities. Non pruritic.

  • CRP markedly elevated.

  • Investigations: neutrophil leukocytosis, thrombocytosis, anaemia, elevated transaminases; very high ferritin
    | Still's | Very high ferritin; not seen in other diseases |
    | SLE | ANA is positive; ANA not positive in AOSD |

  • Characteristic feature: Fusion of wrist joints;

  • Rash mostly affects chest and thighs.

  • Pancytopaenia with bleeding manifestations: purpura, easy bruising, mucosal bleeds. (low fibrinogen levels seen)

  • also ⬆liver enzymes, ⬆Triglycerdies ⬆LDH and ⬇Na levels,

  • Management: High dose IV corticosteroids or High dose IVIG +/- cylcosporine / cyclophosphamide.

  1. Erythrocytosis (Differentiating factor from other haematologic neoplastic diseases is increased red cell mass)
  • JAK2 mutation +ve (in almost all) - usually a point mutation.
  • Increased LDH (?increased turnover)
  • Blood picture: Excess of NCNC red cells but in post-polycythemic myelofibrosis stage => leukoerythroblastic blood picture #leukoerythroblastic blood picture.
- Thrombosis: **renal vein thrombosis is a recognised complication of nephrotic syndrome** (occuring in 33%)

[!INFO] Presentation of renal vein thrombosis:

  • Acute: flank pain, gross / microscopic haematuria, enlarged kidney on USS, elevated LDH with normal liver enzymes.
  • Chronic: Asymptomatic; Usually incidentally found on investigation of pulmonary embolus.

Clinical implications

  • Once infected with Mycobacterium tuberculosis, dialy­sis patients have a 20-fold increased risk of developing active disease.
  • Half of patients have some degree of anergy to the tuberculin skin test.Source

Pan-systolic - ventricle leaks to a lower pressure chamber or vessels - MR, TR, VSD

Types of diastolic murmurs

  • AR - decrescendo, early diastolic murmur heard best at left lower sternal border.

Mid diastolic

  • Austin flint murmur occurs in severe AR and is a late diastolic or presystolic murmur.
    • "low pitched presystolic blubbering"
  • Carey coombs - occurs during acute rheumatic carditis due to mitral valve thickening.
    • low pitched (bell), with the patient in the left lateral decubitus position at end expiration.

Mid diastolic - MS, TS,

  • Acute, asymmetrical, lower limb oligoarthritis days to weeks after infection such as dysentery or some sexually acquired infections.
  • Classic triad: Non-infectious urethritis, Arthritis, Conjunctivitis
  • Mnemonic: AUC (Area under the curve)
  • Triggers: dysentery due to salmonella, shigella, or sexually transmitted chlamydia or ureaplasma.
  • Enthesitis causing plantar fascitis or achilles tendon enthesitis can occur.
  • Sacroilitis and spondylitis can also develop.
  • Sterile conjunctivitis
  • Acute anterior uveitis
  • Dactylitis
  • Many GU symptoms ?due to urethritis including clear discharge.
  • Majority of patients recover in 6 months but 30% develop chronic symtpoms.
  • Management is symptomatic. (NSAIDS, corticosteroids, DMARDS like sulfasalazine and infliximab is NSAIDS don't work or a contraindicated)
  • Usually settles with treatment of the infection.
  • New name is DRESS. "Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms."
  • A severe adverse drug reaction
  • Characterized by extensive skin rash and visceral organ involvement. + lymphadenopathy + eosinophilia + atypical lymphocytosis.
  • Occurs between 2 - 8 weeks after starting the drug. (not immediately)
  • Can occur with many drugs, including antiepileptics.
  • Features:
    • Fever
    • Rash - maculopapular. Mucosal involvement can occur but much less than SJS.
    • Facial oedema
    • Lymphadenopathy
    • Any other organ involvement
      • Commonest is liver
      • AKI, Heart, pulmonary

Diagnosis of active TB

  • Chest X ray - Classic finding: upper lobe cavitation + bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy.
  • Sputum smear: sensitivity = 50 - 80%.
  • Sputum culture : Gold standard - the most sensitive test.
    • But takes 1 - 3 weeks.
  • Nucleic acid amplification test - more sensitive than smear but less than culture. (takes 24-48 hours)
    • This is the Xpert MTB/RIF assay, a real time TB-PCR test.

We are concerned with the true positive rate and true negative rate of a test.

  • true positive rate = sensitivity
  • true negative rate = specificity

[!INFO] interpretation of sensitivity and specificity
SNOUT and SPINS

  • Sn: Sensitive test rules out the disease when it is negative.
  • Sp: specific test rules in a disease when it is positive.

Type 1 and type 2 errors

This part is intuitive:

  • When a test is not sensitive, it has a high false negative rate. (Type 2 error)
  • When a test is not specific, it has a high false positive rate. (Type 1 error)

[!INFO] Type 1 Vs type 2 error

  • When the boy cried wolf for the first time and the villagers believed him : type 1 error
  • When the boy cried wolf for the second time, the villagers didn't believe him : type 2 error.

[!INFO] prerequisite knowledge:

  • What is parametric statistics?
  • The branch of statistics which assumes that underlying population characteristic follows a known distribution which can be described with certain parameters. The most common such distribution is the normal distribution.
  • But other distributions can also be assumed in parametric statistics. (The chi squared distribution, the poisson distrubition etc)
    [!WARNING] Wilcoxon rank sum test is the same as Mann-whitney U test
    Mnemonic: Both have U in the name

t-tests

Assumptions made with regards to independent samples t-tests

  • There is theoretically no minimum sample size but the following must be satisfied.
  • The dependent variable should be continuous (i.e ratio/interval)
  • Independent variable should consist of two categorical groups
  • independence of observations: No relationship between observations within or between groups.
    • Eg: no overlap of participants between the two groups
    • If this is not met, a paired sample t-test should be done.
  • no significant outliers: outliers make the t-test less reliable.
  • Dependent variable should be approximately normally distributed. Note: ordinal scales used in surveys don't yield normally distributed results.
    • Normalcy of data can be tested with the goodness-of-fit tests like the shapiro-wilk test.
  • homogeneity of variances: The variances of data in both groups should be similar.
    Same as Wilcoxon rank sum test
    T-test assumptions: Source

Levels of measurement

Nominal = categorial
No sense of order.
Frequency or percentage is used to summarise.

Ordinal:
Have an order.
But the interval between values is unequal.

Interval / ratio
Things that can be measured

Power of a study

  • The probability of not making a type 2 error
    Or equivalently
  • the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is false.

The probability that a study will detect a difference in measurement between two groups when such a difference actually exists, given a pre-set p alpha and sample size.

[!INFO] Pendrin
Is a key transport protein involved in pathogenesis.

"internal potassium balance".

The transcellular shifts in K+ caused by acid base changes.
Basis: In acidosis, about half the H+ is buffered intracellularly. To maintain electroneutrality, intracellular K+ moves outwards into the ECF.

[!INFO] Hypoaldosteronism
In patients with hypoaldosteronism, for example, the mild metabolic acidosis is primarily due to the associated hyperkalemia
